"(1) (i) The air inside the pressurized dome shimmered with the faint blue haze of recycled oxygen, the metallic tang of ozone lingering after the last storm outside the regolith walls. Levi’s gloved fingers tightened around the rail as the colony’s artificial gravity flickered, a subtle stutter that rippled through the floor beneath his boots. Outside the reinforced glass, the lunar dust glinted like crushed sapphires under the pale sun, but inside, the world felt suddenly unsteady—a sensation that was nothing new, not here.\n(2) (ii) His comm unit buzzed, a low, synthetic hum that cut through the silence. He ignored it, focusing instead on the steady thrum of the transport shuttle docked a hundred meters away. The crew had just finished unloading the new fusion core, and the hum of machinery was supposed to drown out the emptiness of space. Levi Rodriguez.\n(3) But now, a sharp, metallic screech echoed through the corridor, closer than it should be. Levi’s heart skipped. He glanced at the overhead status lights—nothing flashed red, yet the gravity felt wrong, heavy and uneven, as if the floor itself was fighting to stay flat.\n(4) (iii) He hurried toward the maintenance bay, boots clanking, passing engineers in motion-blurred suits who barely registered his approach. Their faces were half-lit by the emergency panels flickering on the walls, casting jagged shadows. The malfunction had begun moments ago, he realized, as the shuttle’s engines shuddered and the. Luna Shackleton Crater Colony. June 14, 2225. witnessed a inertial dampener malfunction."